ericans' racial position helped reinforce the emerging tropes of colorblind racial ideology. In the post–civil rights era, when overt racism was no longer socially acceptable, anti-integration voices utilized the indeterminacy of Mexican American racial identity to frame their opposition to school desegregation. That some Mexican Americans adopted these tropes only reinforced the strength of colorblindness in battles against civil rights in the 1970s.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aMexican AmericansxCivil rightszColoradozDenver. 0aMexican AmericansxEducationzColoradozDenver. 0aRacism in educationzColoradozDenver. 0aRacismzColoradozDenver. 0aSegregation in educationzColoradozDenver. 7aHISTORY / North America.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076649340uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520974746?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520974746423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520974746/original  a978-3-11-076649-3  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles